  "prompt": "\"We think your work speaks for itself, so there's no need to write a cover letter.\" Is this a test from Google interviewers? Should I write a cover letter?",
  "response": "If the interviewers or the job application explicitly state that a cover letter is not required, then there generally isn't a need to write one. It\u2019s possible that the phrase \"We think your work speaks for itself, so there's no need to write a cover letter\" is meant genuinely and not as a test.\n\nHowever, it's also true that the professional world sometimes values going the extra mile. If you believe that a cover letter would significantly enhance your application by highlighting specific experiences, skills, or motivations that aren't fully captured in your resume, you might consider writing one anyway. A well-crafted cover letter can provide context to your resume, show your enthusiasm for the position, and demonstrate your communication skills.\n\nIn conclusion:\n- If they explicitly say not to include one, it's usually best to follow instructions.\n- If there's any ambiguity or if you feel strongly that a cover letter could provide valuable additional information, you could include one as long as you do so thoughtfully and concisely.\n\nRemember to tailor your approach to the specific situation and company culture.",
